2: Regression and Model Validation

date()
## [1] "Sun Jun 12 00:06:14 2022"

This week I am learning about data wrangling and linear regression. For the exercise, I have created the learning2014.txt file by doing data wrangling to the full learning2014 data. As the continuation of that exercise, now I will perform regression analysis to the wrangled data and interpret it.

#reading the data
learning2014 <- read.table("http://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/production/course_2218/datasets/learning2014.txt", sep=",", header=TRUE)
dim(learning2014)
## [1] 166   7
str(learning2014)
## 'data.frame':    166 obs. of  7 variables:
##  $ gender  : chr  "F" "M" "F" "M" ...
##  $ age     : int  53 55 49 53 49 38 50 37 37 42 ...
##  $ attitude: num  3.7 3.1 2.5 3.5 3.7 3.8 3.5 2.9 3.8 2.1 ...
##  $ deep    : num  3.58 2.92 3.5 3.5 3.67 ...
##  $ stra    : num  3.38 2.75 3.62 3.12 3.62 ...
##  $ surf    : num  2.58 3.17 2.25 2.25 2.83 ...
##  $ points  : int  25 12 24 10 22 21 21 31 24 26 ...
  • Here, we can see that our data was collected from 166 students with 7 variables, which are gender, age, attitude, deep, stra, surf, and points.
  • The variable gender is a character data with two values which describes the students gender, F for females and M for males.
  • The variable age is an integer data describing the students age.
  • The variable attitude is a numerical data describing the students attitude towards statistics.
  • Variables deep, stra, and surf each measures the students deep, strategic, and surface approach to learning.
  • Variable points shows us the students exam score
#accessing the libraries
library(ggplot2)
library(GGally)
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'GGally':
##   method from   
##   +.gg   ggplot2
#drawing scatter plot matrix
p <- ggpairs(learning2014, mapping = aes(col=gender, alpha=0.3), lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20)))
p

  • The data from female students are represented in pink while the data from male students are represented in green.
  • The frequency data shows us that we have more data from female students.
  • The highly skewed age graph shows us that most of our respondents are very young although we have a few older respondents.
  • From the correlation score, we can see that the students exam score has the highest correlation to the attitude score. The correlation is positive, which means that students with higher attitude score tends to have higher exam score.
  • The second highest correlation is between the students exam score and the strategic learning measurement. This correlation is also positive, which means that students who measures higher on strategic learning tends to have higher exam score.
  • The third highest correlation is between the students exam score and the surface learning measurement. This time, the correlation is negative, which means that students who measures higher on surface learning tends to have lower exam score.
#linear model with three variables as explanatory variables 
my_model <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra +surf, data = learning2014)
summary(my_model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.1550  -3.4346   0.5156   3.6401  10.8952 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.0171     3.6837   2.991  0.00322 ** 
## attitude      3.3952     0.5741   5.913 1.93e-08 ***
## stra          0.8531     0.5416   1.575  0.11716    
## surf         -0.5861     0.8014  -0.731  0.46563    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.296 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2074, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1927 
## F-statistic: 14.13 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 3.156e-08
  • The Rsquared value is 0.2074; the three explanatory variables together accounts for 20.74% of the variation in the students exam score.
  • The omnibus F statistic has a very low associated p-value, which means that there is a strong evidence that not all three coefficients are zero.
  • The p-values of the explanatory variables imply that attitude is strongly associated with the students exam scores, while strategic and surface learning measurements seem to not associated with the students exam score. Now, we will fit the model with only the significant explanatory variable.
#removing variables that are not statistically significant 
my_model <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
summary(my_model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09
  • The Rsquared value is 0.1906, only a little lower than the first model. Attitude alone accounts for 19.06% of the variation in the students exam score.
  • The regression coefficient of the variable attitude changed a little compared to the previous model, but remain highly significant.
  • The regression coefficient of the variable attitude is 3.5255, which means that for every 1 point increase of the variable attitude, there is 3.5255 increase of the variable points.
  • The fitted model becomes: points = 11.6372 + 3.5255 * attitude
#drawing diagnostic plot
plot(my_model, which=c(1,2,5))

  • The residual vs fitted plot seems to confirm that the fitted model is appropriate. The variability of the residuals does not seem to significantly increase nor decrease with the size of the fitted values.
  • The normal Q-Q plot shows little evidence of departure from linearity, so there is not enough evidence of a departure from normality
  • The residual vs leverage plot shows that there are no influential points in the data, as no observation lies outside of the Cooks distance. This implies that the data does not have any outliers that would impact the models coefficients greatly.

  • Here, we have a data collected from 370 students with 51 variables.
  • This data describes student achievement in secondary education and includes the students grades, demographic, social, and school related information.
  • G3 is the final year grade of the student, while G2 and G1 are respectively the 1st and 2nd period grades.
  • We also have alc_use numeric variable, that shows the average alcohol consumption of the student.
  • The variable high_use is a logical variable that shows if the students alcohol consumption is high.

Choose 4 variables and create personal hypothesis: - goout: students who go out more often would have higher alcohol consumption - sex: males tend to have higher alcohol consumption - absences: students with higher absences would have higher alcohol consumption - studytime: students who spends more time studying would have lower alcohol consumption

#running logistic regression with the chosen variables
m <- glm(high_use ~ goout + sex + absences + studytime, data=alc, family="binomial")
summary(m)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = high_use ~ goout + sex + absences + studytime, 
##     family = "binomial", data = alc)
##

# compute odds ratios (OR)
OR <- coef(m) %>% exp

# compute confidence intervals (CI)
CI <- exp(confint(m))
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
# print out the odds ratios with their confidence intervals
cbind(OR, CI)
##                     OR      2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.04106168 0.01223447 0.1291474
## goout       2.06437847 1.63882768 2.6351100
## sexM        2.31633977 1.36894449 3.9634620
## absences    1.08169564 1.03565150 1.1336977
## studytime   0.64748646 0.45763756 0.8996268
  • The result shows that going out frequency, sex, number of absences, and time spent studying are all significant predictors of students alcohol use.
  • Students with higher score of going out are 2.06 times more likely to have high alcohol consumption, with the 95% confidence interval between 1.64-2.63 times more likely. This is in line with the original hypothesis.
  • Male students are 2.3 times more likely to have higher alcohol consumption than female students, with the 95% confidence interval between 1.37-3.96 times more likely. This is in line with the original hypothesis.
  • Students with higher absences are 1.08 times more likely to have higher alcohol consumption, with the 95% confidence interval between 1.03-1.13 times more likely. Although this variable is highly significant, its odds ratio is not as extreme as it is a numeric variable with a high range of values, and the odds ratio is comparing the n vs n-1 value of the variable, which is only slightly different. In another word, students with n number of absences are 1.08 times more likely to have high alcohol consumption compared to students with n-1 number of absences. This is in line with the original hypothesis.
  • Students who spend more time studying are 0.65 times more likely to have high alcohol consumption, with the 95% confidence interval between 0.46-0.90. As the odds ratio is less than 1, it can also be interpreted as: students who spends more time studying are 1.54 (1/0.65) times less likely to have high alcohol consumption. This is inline with the original hypothesis.
# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   244   15
##    TRUE     62   49
# initialize a plot of 'high_use' versus 'probability' in 'alc'
g <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = probability, y = high_use, col = prediction))

# define the geom as points and draw the plot
g + geom_point()

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction) %>% prop.table %>% addmargins
##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE        Sum
##    FALSE 0.65945946 0.04054054 0.70000000
##    TRUE  0.16756757 0.13243243 0.30000000
##    Sum   0.82702703 0.17297297 1.00000000
# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2081081
  • Only around 20.8% individuals are classified inaccurately, which means that the prediction of this model is a lot better than simple guessing strategy.
  • The proportion of incorrect prediction seems to be higher in high alcohol use group, which may be because the characteristics of individuals with high alcohol use is more diverse.
# compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class= alc$high_use, prob= alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2081081
# K-fold cross-validation
library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = 10)

# average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2108108
  • This model has 0.203 error rate, which is lower than DataCamps model which was 0.26. This means that this model has better set test performance.
